- [Google Maps Platform Billing and Pricing](https://developers.google.com/maps/billing-and-pricing/pricing)
- [API Key Auth and Restrictions](https://developers.google.com/maps/api-security-best-practices)

Use the new one — the legacy Places API can no longer be enabled for new projects.

Here's a breakdown of what's changed and what you should use instead:

## Legacy → Current Autocomplete Migration

The key surface replacements for autocomplete are:

| Legacy | Current |
|---|---|
| `new google.maps.places.Autocomplete(input, ...)` widget | `<gmp-place-autocomplete>` element |
| `autocomplete.addListener("place_changed", ...)` | `element.addEventListener("gmp-select", ...)` |
| `autocomplete.getPlace()` | `placePrediction.toPlace()` from the `gmp-select` event payload |
| `AutocompleteService.getPlacePredictions()` | `AutocompleteSuggestion.fetchAutocompleteSuggestions()` (or use the element) |
| Manual `AutocompleteSessionToken` with the element | Not needed — element manages tokens automatically |

## Why You Must Switch

**New Google Cloud projects can no longer enable the legacy Places API at all.** Existing customers who enabled legacy Places before the cutoff can continue using it, but Google has not published an explicit decommission date. Google's guidance is to migrate now.

## The Recommended Approach: `<gmp-place-autocomplete>`

For most use cases, the `<gmp-place-autocomplete>` web component is the right choice. Here's a minimal working example:

```html
<!-- In your HTML -->
<gmp-place-autocomplete id="autocomplete"></gmp-place-autocomplete>
```

```javascript
const { PlaceAutocompleteElement } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");

const autocompleteEl = document.getElementById("autocomplete");

autocompleteEl.addEventListener("gmp-select", async (event) => {
  const place = await event.placePrediction.toPlace();
  await place.fetchFields({
    fields: ["displayName", "formattedAddress", "location"],
  });

  console.log(place.displayName);
  console.log(place.formattedAddress);
  console.log(place.location.lat(), place.location.lng());
});
```

## Session Token Handling (Cost Optimization)

The `PlaceAutocompleteElement` automatically manages session tokens internally — it "automatically uses `AutocompleteSessionToken`s internally to group the query and selection phases of a user's autocomplete search." You don't need to create or pass one.

If you use the manual REST or `AutocompleteSuggestion.fetchAutocompleteSuggestions()` approach instead, you are required to generate a session token (UUID) and pass it on each autocomplete request, then on the Place Details request that completes the session. Skipping session tokens in manual flows means each keystroke is billed as a standalone autocomplete request.

**Bottom line:** Use `<gmp-place-autocomplete>` for new projects — it's simpler, handles session tokens automatically, and is the only option available to new Cloud projects.

**Sources:**
- [Places API (New)](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/places/web-service/overview)
- [Deprecations and Migration Guide](https://developers.google.com/maps/deprecations)

Great, the search results give a clear and well-sourced answer. Here's the breakdown:

---

**The answer depends on the API you're calling** — but for the classic web service APIs (Geocoding, Directions, etc.), `OVER_QUERY_LIMIT` comes back as **HTTP 200 with the error status in the JSON/XML body**, not as an HTTP-level error code.

### Legacy Web Service APIs (Geocoding, Directions, etc.)

`OVER_QUERY_LIMIT` indicates that you are over your quota. When this happens, the web service stops providing normal responses and switches to returning only the status code `OVER_QUERY_LIMIT` until more usage is allowed again. This scenario can happen within a few seconds if the error was received because your application sent too many requests per minute.

The response is still **HTTP 200**, with the status embedded in the response body like this:

```json
{
  "results": [],
  "status": "OVER_QUERY_LIMIT"
}
```

In rare cases something may go wrong serving your request and you may receive a 4XX or 5XX HTTP response code — but that's for transient server errors, not quota violations. `OVER_QUERY_LIMIT` itself is not one of those cases.

### Routes / Tile APIs (newer)

The newer APIs use standard HTTP semantics more consistently. Common errors include 400 (Invalid argument), 403 (Permission denied), and **429 (Too many requests)** — so rate limiting there surfaces as a proper HTTP 429.

---

### Practical Implication

Because the legacy APIs return HTTP 200 even on quota errors, **you must inspect the `status` field in the response body** — you can't rely solely on the HTTP status code to detect quota issues. Here's a robust retry pattern:

```javascript
async function geocodeWithRetry(address, retries = 3) {
  for (let i = 0; i < retries; i++) {
    try {
      const result = await geocoder.geocode({ address });
      return result;
    } catch (error) {
      if (error.code === "OVER_QUERY_LIMIT" && i < retries - 1) {
        // Exponential backoff: 1s, 2s, 4s...
        await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, Math.pow(2, i) * 1000));
        continue;
      }
      throw error;
    }
  }
}
```

A better approach is to retry with increasing delays between attempts — usually the delay is increased by a multiplicative factor with each attempt, an approach known as Exponential Backoff.

